WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: IVM.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:36.840
[Amit Varma]: So, let's look at history as a linear series of events, one thing following another, with

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:39.300
[Amit Varma]: everything seemingly inevitable.

00:00:39.300 --> 00:00:41.600
[Amit Varma]: But that's the hindsight bias at play.

00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:46.520
[Amit Varma]: When historical events are happening in the present tense, all possibilities seem open,

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:48.560
[Amit Varma]: everything seems chaotic, anything can happen.

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:53.720
[Amit Varma]: Also, there are far more factors at play that determine the course of history, and most

00:00:53.720 --> 00:00:57.880
[Amit Varma]: of those don't make it to the narrative that we later tell about it.

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:02.520
[Amit Varma]: Also, historians come along who look further, who look deeper, and expand that narrative

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:04.200
[Amit Varma]: and our knowledge of the world.

00:01:04.200 --> 00:01:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Srinath Raghavan is one such historian, and Bangladesh is one such subject.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:18.440
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:19.440
