[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:22.520
[Amit Varma]: Great to be here.

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:27.400
[Amit Varma]: So Srinath, I'm going to begin by exploring an angle I sort of explored with, you know,

00:03:27.400 --> 00:03:33.360
[Amit Varma]: when I did a couple of episodes on Gandhi with Ramchandra Buha, and where I asked him

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:38.480
[Amit Varma]: about the difficulty of being a historian, given that we are wired for what is called

00:03:38.480 --> 00:03:42.680
[Amit Varma]: the hindsight bias, that when you look back at history, everything seems inevitable.

00:03:42.680 --> 00:03:48.280
[Amit Varma]: And it struck me when I was reading your book on Bangladesh, 1971, that that's one of your

00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:54.360
[Amit Varma]: starting premises for the book is that the that sense of inevitability plays out especially

00:03:54.360 --> 00:03:56.800
[Amit Varma]: strongly with Bangladesh.

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:01.040
[Amit Varma]: And it wasn't at all as inevitable and you examine the various reasons why.

00:04:01.040 --> 00:04:04.980
[Amit Varma]: But just as a general question, if I may pose the same question to you that I posed to Ram,

00:04:04.980 --> 00:04:10.120
[Amit Varma]: how do you sort of mentally take that step back from that sense of inevitability?

00:04:10.120 --> 00:04:15.000
[Guest]: Well, so historians have a saying that, you know, life is lived forwards, but understood

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:16.000
[Guest]: backwards, right?

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.420
[Guest]: So in a sense, the challenge for the historian is how do you sort of try and find some kind

00:04:20.420 --> 00:04:25.760
[Guest]: of a point, which does not exclusively privilege hindsight, but hindsight is absolutely important,

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:28.640
[Guest]: because that's the only way you can make sense of things together.

00:04:28.640 --> 00:04:33.840
[Guest]: And to have that sense of contingency, but also causality in play, is I think a bit of

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:35.840
[Guest]: a balance that you strike as you go along.

00:04:35.840 --> 00:04:37.240
[Guest]: In a sense, there is no formula for it.

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:40.360
[Guest]: It's more of a craft and how you sort of approach things, right?

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:44.200
[Guest]: So this is great historian of the French Revolution, who is to say that, you know, before it happens,

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:46.080
[Guest]: every revolution seems impossible.

00:04:46.080 --> 00:04:48.120
[Guest]: But after it happens, it seems inevitable, right?

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:52.080
[Guest]: And that that's true of most great things like the Bangladesh emergence of an independent

00:04:52.080 --> 00:04:53.280
[Guest]: country and so on.

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:58.000
[Guest]: So the challenge for me in writing this book was precisely to come to terms with that kind

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.400
[Guest]: of a meta question of saying, how are we going to tell the story without making it all seem

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:06.280
[Guest]: as if it was so predetermined, which in some ways also takes away agency from people at

00:05:06.280 --> 00:05:08.880
[Guest]: the end of the day, history is made by people themselves.

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:11.080
[Amit Varma]: And specifically, how did you arrive at Bangladesh?

00:05:11.080 --> 00:05:16.760
[Guest]: Well, I was actually working on a PhD thesis focusing on Indian foreign policy in the sort

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:20.120
[Guest]: of early years, primarily focusing on the Nehru period.

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:22.120
[Guest]: And I was working in the Nehru Memorial Museum and Library.

00:05:22.120 --> 00:05:23.720
[Guest]: This was in the early 2000s.

00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:27.460
[Guest]: And at that point of time, the papers of P. N. Huxer, who was Indira Gandhi's principal

00:05:27.460 --> 00:05:32.140
[Guest]: secretary during that period, were actually sort of deposited and made available to scholars.

00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:35.320
[Guest]: So I was one of the first people to sort of go through them, you know, it's a very large

00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:36.320
[Guest]: collection.

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:39.240
[Guest]: Lately, we've had Jairam Ramesh writing a biography of P. N. Huxer, which makes very

00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:40.840
[Guest]: good thorough use of all those sources.

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:44.760
[Guest]: But I think I was one of the first people to actually see that.

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:47.760
[Guest]: And it very quickly struck me that there was very interesting material on the Bangladesh

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:52.680
[Guest]: crisis, which suggested very different points of view, even ab initio.

00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:55.400
[Guest]: And then I decided to sort of make that a project.

00:05:55.400 --> 00:06:00.360
[Guest]: But it also struck me that it would be useful to widen out the perspective and not just

00:06:00.360 --> 00:06:04.320
[Guest]: do an India-centered account of how the Indians approached the crisis, but to look at the

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:08.920
[Guest]: crisis as a whole, to understand this very important historical event in post-colonial

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:14.000
[Guest]: South Asia, which is the emergence of Bangladesh, and to sort of do it on a much wider canvas.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.040
[Guest]: So that's how the project really began.

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:19.480
[Guest]: And then I started working in a range of other archives, you know, I've sort of worked in

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:24.120
[Guest]: Britain, America, Canada, Australia, the Soviet Union, Germany.

00:06:24.120 --> 00:06:29.040
[Guest]: So all of these archives then kind of opened up a much more sort of multifaceted sort of

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:32.480
[Guest]: portrait of the period and of that particular event itself.

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:37.080
[Amit Varma]: And just as an aside, your book is full of these illuminations and insights from the

00:06:37.080 --> 00:06:39.520
[Amit Varma]: so to say bit players like Huxer, D.P.

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:40.520
[Amit Varma]: Dhar, P.N.

00:06:40.520 --> 00:06:44.760
[Amit Varma]: Dhar, who all sound like, you know, fairly evolved intellects, you know, not what you

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:49.560
[Amit Varma]: would expect the typical, what the stereotype of the Babu or the bureaucrat is.

00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:54.760
[Amit Varma]: And that that was also fascinating to me to see those sort of influences upon our Prime

00:06:54.760 --> 00:06:55.760
[Guest]: Minister.

00:06:55.760 --> 00:06:56.760
[Guest]: Oh, yeah, absolutely.

00:06:56.760 --> 00:07:01.160
[Guest]: And one of the sort of key strengths, which Indira Gandhi had, particularly in her early

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:05.480
[Guest]: period of her sort of prime ministerial career, was to be able to accumulate this kind of

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:10.920
[Guest]: very high quality talent of civil servants, people with, you know, sort of, you know,

00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:14.720
[Guest]: foreign policy experience with intelligence background, to be able to sort of assist her.

00:07:14.720 --> 00:07:18.440
[Guest]: And at least in the case of the Bangladesh crisis, I think these people were not just

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:21.120
[Guest]: bit players, they were very important, you know, and someone like P.N.

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:25.760
[Guest]: Huxer was literally sort of the person holding various strands of crisis management together

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:29.720
[Guest]: on behalf of the Prime Minister, of course, and looking through those notes and, you know,

00:07:29.720 --> 00:07:33.200
[Guest]: the letters that they wrote to each other about what Mrs. Gandhi told them in certain

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:35.000
[Guest]: meetings and so on was absolutely fascinating.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:39.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, much more erudite and crisp and better articulated than many op-eds of the day, which

00:07:39.560 --> 00:07:40.560
[Amit Varma]: you might find.

00:07:40.560 --> 00:07:45.360
[Amit Varma]: So I'm intrigued by, you know, an early sentence in your book, which I found in the introduction

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:49.400
[Amit Varma]: to your book, which is, quote, professional historians of South Asia remain reluctant

00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:52.720
[Amit Varma]: to venture beyond the boundary of 1947, stop quote.

00:07:52.720 --> 00:07:53.720
[Guest]: What do you mean by this?

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:54.720
[Guest]: Can you elaborate?

00:07:54.720 --> 00:07:59.360
[Guest]: What I meant to say was that the study of South Asian history, as it happens in universities,

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:04.760
[Guest]: as done by historians who sort of teach and research in sort of universities and so on,

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:09.240
[Guest]: is still very much focused either on the colonial period or the pre-colonial past.

00:08:09.240 --> 00:08:13.120
[Guest]: The immediate sort of post-independence period and or the post-colonial period in South Asia

00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:17.560
[Guest]: as a whole still remains something that historians are reluctant to touch, partly because they

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:21.800
[Guest]: see it as too close to their time, partly because the archives for the older period

00:08:21.800 --> 00:08:26.160
[Guest]: are much better organized, more easily, you know, if you want to work on some topic to

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:29.440
[Guest]: do with British India, you can go to the British Library in London, you can look at the National

00:08:29.440 --> 00:08:33.280
[Guest]: Archives in India, you'd get a reasonable, whereas for the post-colonial period, especially

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:37.080
[Guest]: when I was working on the book, things have changed a little bit since then.

00:08:37.080 --> 00:08:40.600
[Guest]: The official archives were almost, you know, had close to zero holdings.

00:08:40.600 --> 00:08:43.840
[Guest]: So you had to sort of go through private papers, which is what I was doing, you know, Luxor

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:49.440
[Guest]: and others, and then use various other kinds of official archives from other countries.

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:52.320
[Guest]: So you, in a sense, that remains a challenge.

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:56.280
[Guest]: The second thing is that, you know, there is some kind of a sort of a tacit intellectual

00:08:56.280 --> 00:09:00.440
[Guest]: or whatever academic division of labor, which has happened, which is to say that historians

00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:04.320
[Guest]: typically look at everything before independence, whereas, you know, it's the political scientists

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:08.080
[Guest]: or international relations scholars who look at the more immediate past.

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:12.640
[Guest]: But I think, you know, that then leaves out a very large arena of our contemporary existence,

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:16.920
[Guest]: which I think needs to be bought under the, you know, the domain of history proper and

00:09:16.920 --> 00:09:19.080
[Guest]: of historical investigation and writing.

00:09:19.080 --> 00:09:22.760
[Guest]: I'm happy to say that since I wrote those words, I mean, things do seem to be moving,

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:25.120
[Guest]: though not as quickly as we'd like it to.

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:29.800
[Guest]: But I think we definitely have a range of books now coming out, which also try and treat

00:09:29.800 --> 00:09:34.160
[Guest]: the sort of post-independence, post-colonial period in the same historical fashion as you

00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:36.360
[Guest]: would do with anything in the distant past.

00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:41.160
[Amit Varma]: And I'd imagine without the bedrock of history, even political science then has a problem

00:09:41.160 --> 00:09:42.800
[Guest]: just dealing with the material, right?

00:09:42.800 --> 00:09:46.520
[Guest]: Well, I mean, I think a big part of the problem with a lot of Indian political science writing

00:09:46.520 --> 00:09:50.120
[Guest]: is precisely that it's very ahistorical and, you know, tends to treat the present as if

00:09:50.120 --> 00:09:51.680
[Guest]: it does not have a past.

00:09:51.680 --> 00:09:56.480
[Guest]: And that, you know, the way that institutions, structures, and processes have evolved historically

00:09:56.480 --> 00:10:00.760
[Guest]: is somehow not of any moment or concern, that the only thing which matters is what is the

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:01.760
[Guest]: dynamic today.

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:07.160
[Guest]: And I think that that ahistorical quality is, I think, been one of the significant drawbacks

00:10:07.160 --> 00:10:09.960
[Guest]: of Indian political science writing.

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:13.040
[Guest]: But at the same time, I think the best Indian political scientists are people who have sort

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:18.040
[Guest]: of, you know, used historical knowledge and historical materials, really, to throw light

00:10:18.040 --> 00:10:21.520
[Guest]: on political processes in more closer periods of time.

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:22.800
[Amit Varma]: And could the converse also be true?

00:10:22.800 --> 00:10:26.080
[Amit Varma]: Like as a historian, do you sometimes feel that you're wearing the hat of a political

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:28.320
[Amit Varma]: scientist also when writing parts of your text?

00:10:28.320 --> 00:10:32.560
[Guest]: Well, the way I sort of tend to approach all of these things is to say that, you know,

00:10:32.560 --> 00:10:35.640
[Guest]: not just political science, but social sciences more broadly are very important for me because

00:10:35.640 --> 00:10:39.000
[Guest]: that gives me heuristic devices with which I approach the archives.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.160
[Guest]: You know, archives and sources don't tell you any stories, you have to ask questions

00:10:42.160 --> 00:10:43.160
[Guest]: of them, you know.

00:10:43.160 --> 00:10:47.440
[Guest]: And for that, you need to have some questions which come out of broader conceptual theoretical

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:48.440
[Guest]: sort of basis.

00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:52.840
[Guest]: Now, you know, I don't go out with a view of trying to prove or disprove this or that

00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:53.840
[Guest]: theory.

00:10:53.840 --> 00:10:57.440
[Guest]: But as a heuristic device, I think social sciences are very important for the historian's

00:10:57.440 --> 00:10:58.440
[Guest]: craft.

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:02.120
[Guest]: But of course, you know, in terms of my own choice, I still prefer the narrative, which

00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:06.480
[Guest]: I think is the domain in which history is best explored and written and presented.

00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:09.560
[Guest]: And so I choose the narrative as the main device through which to tell the story.

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:13.520
[Amit Varma]: So is there sort of a fine balance there that a historian needs to maintain between the

00:11:13.520 --> 00:11:17.720
[Amit Varma]: narrative that they're presenting and the perspectives that they might wish to bear

00:11:17.720 --> 00:11:18.720
[Guest]: upon that narrative?

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:19.720
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:22.880
[Guest]: So, you know, historical narratives, contrary to sort of what, you know, other social sciences

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:25.600
[Guest]: typically tend to think are not just about telling a story, right?

00:11:25.600 --> 00:11:28.120
[Guest]: I mean, you're trying to make a causal argument.

00:11:28.120 --> 00:11:32.440
[Guest]: I think the central difference between, say, most other social sciences and histories,

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:36.920
[Guest]: and I say most because there are exceptions, is that historians are interested in change,

00:11:36.920 --> 00:11:40.200
[Guest]: whereas other social sciences are typically interested in trying to find longer term continuities,

00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:41.200
[Guest]: right?

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:44.280
[Guest]: So they may use historical materials, but with a view to saying so and so process or

00:11:44.280 --> 00:11:47.520
[Guest]: so and so pattern is recurrent, if these are the initial conditions, these are likely to

00:11:47.520 --> 00:11:48.520
[Guest]: be the outcomes, right?

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:50.680
[Guest]: So, so that is the kind of exercise that they are engaged in.

00:11:50.680 --> 00:11:54.480
[Guest]: Whereas for historians, the challenge is not that we're not interested in generalization,

00:11:54.480 --> 00:11:55.480
[Guest]: we are.

00:11:55.480 --> 00:11:58.080
[Guest]: But the bigger problem that you're interested in isn't change.

00:11:58.080 --> 00:11:59.120
[Guest]: How does change happen?

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:02.660
[Guest]: How does a country like Pakistan break up into two parts is exactly the kind of questions

00:12:02.660 --> 00:12:04.160
[Amit Varma]: that historians are drawn to.

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:07.240
[Amit Varma]: And getting back to the breakup of Pakistan, again, early in your book, you say that the

00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:11.520
[Amit Varma]: typical prisms through when one looks at Bangladesh are insularity and determinism, we've already

00:12:11.520 --> 00:12:15.840
[Amit Varma]: spoken about determinism and by insularity, I guess you mean that, you know, people tend

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:20.880
[Amit Varma]: to think of it as either something that concerns Bangladesh alone, or it's an India Pakistan

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:26.280
[Amit Varma]: dynamic and what your book tries to bring out is that there are sort of these geopolitical

00:12:26.280 --> 00:12:31.960
[Amit Varma]: waves of events and, you know, all with their unintended consequences, which are sweeping

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:38.120
[Amit Varma]: through at the time and Bangladesh is really a result of those, I mean, as you said later,

00:12:38.120 --> 00:12:42.160
[Amit Varma]: it's far from being predestined, it's a product of conjuncture and contingency, choice and

00:12:42.160 --> 00:12:43.160
[Guest]: chance.

00:12:43.160 --> 00:12:44.160
[Guest]: Yeah, that's true.

00:12:44.160 --> 00:12:49.040
[Guest]: I mean, in a sense that much of the writing on the creation of Bangladesh, it tends to

00:12:49.040 --> 00:12:53.360
[Guest]: be either from the perspective of trying to tell the story of how Bangladeshi or Bengali

00:12:53.360 --> 00:12:57.800
[Guest]: nationalism sort of rose and, you know, attained its destiny as an independent nation, or it

00:12:57.800 --> 00:13:03.880
[Guest]: is about saying why Pakistan, as it was in 1947, kind of was an unworkable project and

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:04.880
[Guest]: so on.

00:13:04.880 --> 00:13:08.560
[Guest]: So there is an implicit sort of teleology and determinism, which is built into most

00:13:08.560 --> 00:13:14.680
[Guest]: of our storylines to greater and lesser extents, but that's the standard way in which we think.

00:13:14.680 --> 00:13:17.560
[Guest]: And of course, in India, we have our own story of, you know, this being the most important

00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:22.920
[Guest]: sort of moment of India sort of, you know, falsifying the two nation theory and so on.

00:13:22.920 --> 00:13:26.400
[Guest]: Now, I don't for a minute say that any of these narratives are strong.

00:13:26.400 --> 00:13:30.120
[Guest]: What I want to say is that they are incomplete, and that if you really want a more satisfactory

00:13:30.120 --> 00:13:35.560
[Guest]: explanation of why this particular momentous event occurred, then you have to place it

00:13:35.560 --> 00:13:40.320
[Guest]: not just within a national or a regional frame, but actually in something of a global, it's

00:13:40.320 --> 00:13:43.000
[Guest]: an international and transnational frame.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:45.520
[Amit Varma]: And that's what really the book tends to do.

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:51.240
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, all of this, all of what happened in Bangladesh in 71 has its roots, obviously,

00:13:51.240 --> 00:13:57.280
[Amit Varma]: in the 60s under Ayub Khan, and specifically in the context of, say, 1968, when the student

00:13:57.280 --> 00:14:02.400
[Amit Varma]: rebellion start and all of that, you talk about the three historical processes that

00:14:02.400 --> 00:14:07.840
[Amit Varma]: shaped the global context of those years, the first being decolonization.

00:14:07.840 --> 00:14:09.560
[Guest]: Can you tell me a little bit more about that?

00:14:09.560 --> 00:14:14.920
[Guest]: Well, decolonization, you know, obviously, is a breakup of the old sort of European empires

00:14:14.920 --> 00:14:19.560
[Guest]: in the post Second World War period, India was in the first wave of decolonization.

00:14:19.560 --> 00:14:24.200
[Guest]: But by the late 1960s, you had several other countries across Asia and Africa, which have

00:14:24.200 --> 00:14:29.160
[Guest]: gone through, you know, process of decolonization, but which are also in their postcolonial existence

00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:33.760
[Guest]: coming up with various forms of other kinds of issues, borders, ethnicities, various kinds

00:14:33.760 --> 00:14:38.200
[Guest]: of rivalries left behind by older forms of colonial control, and so on.

00:14:38.200 --> 00:14:42.860
[Guest]: So in a sense, what is happening in Bangladesh is therefore best understood as a continuation

00:14:42.860 --> 00:14:46.280
[Guest]: of this larger process of decolonization, even though it is happening within the context

00:14:46.280 --> 00:14:50.100
[Guest]: of a country which is already, you know, out of colonial control, which is Pakistan.

00:14:50.100 --> 00:14:54.080
[Guest]: But nevertheless, the imperatives and the processes seem to me to be very similar to

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:57.280
[Guest]: what was happening with a number of other countries, particularly in Africa at that

00:14:57.280 --> 00:14:58.280
[Guest]: point of time.

00:14:58.280 --> 00:15:00.880
[Guest]: So it is very important, therefore, to sort of put it into that frame.

00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:01.880
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:15:01.880 --> 00:15:04.200
[Amit Varma]: And the second process you mentioned, the frame of the Cold War.

00:15:04.200 --> 00:15:07.960
[Guest]: Yeah, the Cold War is again, you know, something which depending on when you want to date it

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:12.180
[Guest]: starts somewhere after the Second World War and before the late 1940s.

00:15:12.180 --> 00:15:17.240
[Guest]: And the Cold War is typically understood as a sort of a geopolitical and ideological rivalry

00:15:17.240 --> 00:15:22.080
[Guest]: between the United States and its allies, the so-called free world, and the Soviet Union

00:15:22.080 --> 00:15:24.520
[Guest]: and its allies, the so-called communist bloc.

00:15:24.520 --> 00:15:28.760
[Guest]: But what is interesting is that by the late 1960s, you know, the Cold War no longer looks

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:31.800
[Guest]: like this contest between two rigidly organized blocs.

00:15:31.800 --> 00:15:36.600
[Guest]: There is a lot of sort of, you know, moving and, you know, turning around of pieces within

00:15:36.600 --> 00:15:37.680
[Guest]: each of these blocs.

00:15:37.680 --> 00:15:41.040
[Guest]: And one of the big important things, of course, was the split between the Chinese and the

00:15:41.040 --> 00:15:44.480
[Guest]: Soviet Union, which was already coming to the fore by that time, and which plays an

00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:47.280
[Guest]: important role in the story of Bangladesh as well.

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:50.400
[Guest]: So in a sense, it was important, therefore, to suggest that, you know, this was an important

00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:55.320
[Guest]: moment in the Cold War, the realignment of the sort of important pieces of the Cold War

00:15:55.320 --> 00:16:00.560
[Guest]: geopolitics, the waning of some of the ideological competition in the context of the Cold War,

00:16:00.560 --> 00:16:05.000
[Guest]: and how that impacts on an event which is not anywhere in the center of things where

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:06.800
[Guest]: the Cold War was playing out, which is in South Asia.

00:16:06.800 --> 00:16:10.400
[Amit Varma]: Oh, and as you go on to sort of talk about in the book, and we'll discuss in the second

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:14.480
[Amit Varma]: half of this podcast, right, you know, that that simplistic notion that many people have

00:16:14.480 --> 00:16:19.320
[Amit Varma]: and that indeed I had before I read this book that, oh, the US was siding with Pakistan

00:16:19.320 --> 00:16:22.640
[Amit Varma]: and the Soviet Union was with India and blah, blah, blah is actually not true at all.

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:27.200
[Amit Varma]: There were there was a lot of sort of negotiations and to's and fro's happening in this period

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:31.400
[Amit Varma]: with China playing a major part, but I will come to that later in the podcast.

00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:33.600
[Amit Varma]: The next process you mentioned, globalization.

00:16:33.600 --> 00:16:38.840
[Guest]: Yeah, so, you know, decolonization and Cold War, I think are, you know, you can reasonably

00:16:38.840 --> 00:16:40.760
[Guest]: sort of have a sense of what they are.

00:16:40.760 --> 00:16:44.560
[Guest]: But globalization is something that we, at least in our current context, tend to think

00:16:44.560 --> 00:16:47.320
[Guest]: of as something which is very much a post Cold War kind of a moment, right?

00:16:47.320 --> 00:16:52.240
[Guest]: I mean, you want to think about Francis Fukuyama sometime in 1989 announcing the end of history,

00:16:52.240 --> 00:16:55.560
[Guest]: saying that all kinds of, you know, ideological rivalries are coming out.

00:16:55.560 --> 00:17:00.520
[Guest]: That is the moment when Americans sort of attempt to, you know, to create an integrated

00:17:00.520 --> 00:17:03.840
[Guest]: capitalist global economy really takes off and so on.

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:07.240
[Guest]: But one of the things which historians have been pointing to us, and I sort of picked

00:17:07.240 --> 00:17:11.600
[Guest]: up on that literature and built it up, was to say that, you know, what we think of as

00:17:11.600 --> 00:17:16.640
[Guest]: the current wave of globalization, you know, actually is something which begins in the

00:17:16.640 --> 00:17:21.120
[Guest]: early 70s and late 1960s, early 70s is when the first, you know, real wave of sort of

00:17:21.120 --> 00:17:22.640
[Guest]: globalization begins.

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:27.240
[Guest]: By which I mean that there are a number of, you know, events and processes which are coming

00:17:27.240 --> 00:17:31.600
[Guest]: together, which are bringing disparate parts of the world in some sort of communication

00:17:31.600 --> 00:17:32.880
[Guest]: with one another, right?

00:17:32.880 --> 00:17:36.620
[Guest]: So you have the huge explosion of air travel during that period, so people are traveling

00:17:36.620 --> 00:17:40.960
[Guest]: to one place another, the whole story of containerization and so on, you know, already sort of starting

00:17:40.960 --> 00:17:41.960
[Guest]: to take off.

00:17:41.960 --> 00:17:46.360
[Guest]: There's a huge standardization of various kinds of, you know, economic processes, but

00:17:46.360 --> 00:17:48.040
[Guest]: also other kinds of things.

00:17:48.040 --> 00:17:53.640
[Guest]: There is a much greater spread of non-governmental organizations which are trying to bring standardization

00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:54.640
[Guest]: even in terms of values, right?

00:17:54.640 --> 00:17:58.360
[Guest]: I mean, the rise of something like human rights, for instance, happens in a much more global

00:17:58.360 --> 00:18:00.360
[Guest]: context in the same period.

00:18:00.360 --> 00:18:04.680
[Guest]: So in that sense, not just as a process of economic globalization and integration, but

00:18:04.680 --> 00:18:10.040
[Guest]: as one where events and processes which happen in one part of the world are quite tightly

00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:11.760
[Guest]: linked to what is happening elsewhere.

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:15.680
[Guest]: And it seemed to me that this phenomenon is very well established already by the late

00:18:15.680 --> 00:18:16.680
[Guest]: 1960s.

00:18:16.680 --> 00:18:19.940
[Guest]: Of course, contemporary forms of globalization evolved historically from there on.

00:18:19.940 --> 00:18:22.220
[Guest]: But that was a very important moment when this began.

00:18:22.220 --> 00:18:25.560
[Guest]: And again, as I point out in the book, this had important implications for the way the

00:18:25.560 --> 00:18:27.240
[Amit Varma]: Bangladesh crisis plays out.

00:18:27.240 --> 00:18:31.560
[Amit Varma]: And elsewhere, you point out about how there was sort of a technological explosion during

00:18:31.560 --> 00:18:32.560
[Amit Varma]: this time.

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:35.720
[Amit Varma]: One of the first televisions came to Pakistan in 1968.

00:18:35.720 --> 00:18:39.240
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, it was a sort of an inflection point for this kind of cultural globalization,

00:18:39.240 --> 00:18:42.360
[Amit Varma]: which seemed to me, you know, when I was reading it, that is very analogous to the current

00:18:42.360 --> 00:18:47.920
[Amit Varma]: day, when social media has, you know, sort of led to a similar sort of deepening of that

00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:49.440
[Amit Varma]: whole process of cultural globalization.

00:18:49.440 --> 00:18:55.960
[Amit Varma]: Give me a little bit of context into what Pakistan was like in 68.

00:18:55.960 --> 00:18:59.800
[Amit Varma]: Ayub Khan had already been in charge for many years.

00:18:59.800 --> 00:19:03.760
[Amit Varma]: People often said that, you know, under him, there was sort of a new Pakistan, which was

00:19:03.760 --> 00:19:04.760
[Amit Varma]: emerging.

00:19:04.760 --> 00:19:07.680
[Amit Varma]: Ayub himself stood for stability and growth.

00:19:07.680 --> 00:19:11.560
[Amit Varma]: He got a fair amount of support from the US, which is, you know, a process that started

00:19:11.560 --> 00:19:12.560
[Amit Varma]: a decade earlier.

00:19:12.560 --> 00:19:17.960
[Amit Varma]: Just lay the context for me coming to 1968, you know, when it might seem, say, in the

00:19:17.960 --> 00:19:20.440
[Amit Varma]: mid to late 60s, that this guy's going to be here for a long time.

00:19:20.440 --> 00:19:22.440
[Guest]: And then, like you said, overnight, he's gone.

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:27.440
[Guest]: Well, 1960s are a very important and interesting decade in the history of Pakistan, which is

00:19:27.440 --> 00:19:31.600
[Guest]: to say that, you know, that was a decade when Pakistan registered, at least in terms of

00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:38.200
[Guest]: GDP growth and quite an extraordinary accomplishment of almost averaging about 6% annual GDP growth

00:19:38.200 --> 00:19:39.560
[Guest]: over that decade.

00:19:39.560 --> 00:19:44.880
[Guest]: That was possible because, you know, Ayub Khan was sort of following a set of, you know,

00:19:44.880 --> 00:19:49.440
[Guest]: planned economic policies, which were actually a lot of it was crafted by American economists,

00:19:49.440 --> 00:19:53.080
[Guest]: the Harvard Advisory Group and others who were helping him, you know, do it.

00:19:53.080 --> 00:19:57.160
[Guest]: And Pakistan also got onto the bandwagon of the Green Revolution even before India did.

00:19:57.160 --> 00:19:58.760
[Guest]: They started in the early 60s itself.

00:19:58.760 --> 00:20:02.720
[Guest]: So, in that sense, this was a decade when Pakistan actually witnessed considerable levels

00:20:02.720 --> 00:20:04.320
[Guest]: of economic growth.

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:09.080
[Guest]: But that economic growth as by the end of the decade was, it was becoming was, was very,

00:20:09.080 --> 00:20:10.080
[Guest]: very lopsided.

00:20:10.080 --> 00:20:13.240
[Guest]: And some of the Harvard economists who are advising the Pakistanis themselves conceded

00:20:13.240 --> 00:20:18.360
[Guest]: that, in a sense, their policies were aimed towards fostering capital accumulation and

00:20:18.360 --> 00:20:19.600
[Guest]: investment.

00:20:19.600 --> 00:20:21.960
[Guest]: But the groups which are capable of doing it were very small.

00:20:21.960 --> 00:20:24.960
[Guest]: In fact, at one point of time, the head of the Pakistani Planning Commission said that

00:20:24.960 --> 00:20:29.520
[Guest]: there were just 22 families in Pakistan, which accounted for something like 85 to 90% of

00:20:29.520 --> 00:20:30.520
[Guest]: the country's wealth.

00:20:30.520 --> 00:20:34.000
[Guest]: So there was an extraordinary concentration of wealth by conscious government policy,

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.400
[Guest]: you know, giving tax breaks, you know, basically all the things that you want to do to enable

00:20:37.400 --> 00:20:41.240
[Guest]: capitalist accumulation and investment was the game.

00:20:41.240 --> 00:20:47.160
[Guest]: And that, in the Pakistani context, got exacerbated because of the sort of geographical disparities

00:20:47.160 --> 00:20:49.660
[Guest]: between West Pakistan and East Pakistan.

00:20:49.660 --> 00:20:54.000
[Guest]: So if you can just take a step back, right, so in 1947, when Pakistan is created, you

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:58.520
[Guest]: have this kind of completely geographically anomalous entity coming out, which is West

00:20:58.520 --> 00:21:03.920
[Guest]: Pakistan, which is today's Pakistan and, you know, East Pakistan, which is today's Bangladesh,

00:21:03.920 --> 00:21:07.480
[Guest]: being under sort of one particular sort of, you know, being the same country and in a

00:21:07.480 --> 00:21:08.480
[Guest]: similar regime.

00:21:08.480 --> 00:21:13.040
[Guest]: In fact, in this novel, Shame, Salman Rushdie has this fantastic line where he says that

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:14.840
[Guest]: United Pakistan was a strange bird.

00:21:14.840 --> 00:21:16.880
[Guest]: It was two wings without a body, right?

00:21:16.880 --> 00:21:19.600
[Guest]: Because that body was effectively, you were separated by India.

00:21:19.600 --> 00:21:24.040
[Guest]: So there was this tendency to assume, therefore, that, you know, divide between these two parts

00:21:24.040 --> 00:21:27.760
[Guest]: is not just geographic, but, you know, there was sort of economic disparities.

00:21:27.760 --> 00:21:30.840
[Guest]: East Pakistan was the more sort of, you know, commodity producing area.

00:21:30.840 --> 00:21:35.360
[Guest]: Things like jute used to grow there, exports of those in, you know, earned dollars for

00:21:35.360 --> 00:21:38.280
[Guest]: the Pakistani government, but a lot of the investment and industrial development was

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:40.080
[Guest]: actually happening in the West.

00:21:40.080 --> 00:21:44.480
[Guest]: So there was this regional disparity of economic growth as well, not just in terms of class

00:21:44.480 --> 00:21:45.480
[Guest]: sort of differentiation.

00:21:45.480 --> 00:21:48.520
[Guest]: And there were, of course, language issues, like Urdu being the official language.

00:21:48.520 --> 00:21:52.520
[Guest]: And that sort of language issue was in some ways the first major trigger, right?

00:21:52.520 --> 00:21:57.200
[Guest]: The first sort of major movement in East Pakistan actually happens over the fact that Bengali

00:21:57.200 --> 00:22:01.600
[Guest]: is not initially accepted as an important language of the state, which is not just a

00:22:01.600 --> 00:22:03.960
[Guest]: cultural issue, but it's one to do with employment and stuff.

00:22:03.960 --> 00:22:07.560
[Guest]: So if you want to become a Pakistani civil servant, you will have to write exams in Urdu,

00:22:07.560 --> 00:22:08.560
[Guest]: right?

00:22:08.560 --> 00:22:10.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, so in a sense, you know, your knowledge of Bengali doesn't count for very much.

00:22:10.840 --> 00:22:15.640
[Amit Varma]: So all this time, it's interesting to me that, you know, that the eastern wing of Pakistan

00:22:15.640 --> 00:22:16.640
[Guest]: is actually more populous.

00:22:16.640 --> 00:22:21.520
[Guest]: Yeah, it is in terms of just number of people, eastern wing of Pakistan was always more populous.

00:22:21.520 --> 00:22:25.480
[Guest]: And, you know, a united Pakistan did not have an election till 1970.

00:22:25.480 --> 00:22:29.480
[Guest]: But if you had by that point of time, majority of the electorate was also in East Pakistan,

00:22:29.480 --> 00:22:30.480
[Guest]: right?

00:22:30.480 --> 00:22:34.640
[Guest]: So, so in a sense, the fact that normal democratic pressures were not bought to bear in this

00:22:34.640 --> 00:22:39.320
[Guest]: period allowed this kind of, you know, disparate economic growth to happen.

00:22:39.320 --> 00:22:41.360
[Guest]: And the diversity between the two regions was there.

00:22:41.360 --> 00:22:45.880
[Guest]: So, you know, it's, it's again, what is ironic and fascinating about this period is that,

00:22:45.880 --> 00:22:49.400
[Guest]: you know, the period of Pakistan's sort of immense, you know, an impressive sort of economic

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:51.440
[Guest]: growth in the 1960s.

00:22:51.440 --> 00:22:55.440
[Guest]: The economists who are there in the Pakistani Planning Commission are primarily of Bengali

00:22:55.440 --> 00:22:56.440
[Guest]: origin.

00:22:56.440 --> 00:22:57.440
[Guest]: Oh, yeah.

00:22:57.440 --> 00:23:01.000
[Guest]: And by the end of the decade, it is those economists who are coming up with this critique

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:05.680
[Guest]: of the economic system of Pakistan as effectively a neo-colonial one.

00:23:05.680 --> 00:23:09.400
[Guest]: They say that East Pakistan has become a commodity producing area, like all old colonies used

00:23:09.400 --> 00:23:10.400
[Guest]: to be.

00:23:10.400 --> 00:23:14.640
[Guest]: And all the sort of, you know, stuff in terms of, you know, new industries, investment,

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:17.040
[Guest]: etc. is primarily happening in the West.

00:23:17.040 --> 00:23:20.360
[Guest]: So and then East then becomes a importer of the commodities of the West.

00:23:20.360 --> 00:23:24.720
[Guest]: And it's in that context that a lot of these arguments came to be crystallized and the

00:23:24.720 --> 00:23:28.520
[Guest]: relationship came to be seen as fundamentally a neo-colonial one.

00:23:28.520 --> 00:23:32.960
[Amit Varma]: In fact, a little later, there's a quote from Mujib, which I kind of mark down, which is

00:23:32.960 --> 00:23:37.500
[Amit Varma]: quote, the basic truth that every Bengali has felt in his bones, that we have been treated

00:23:37.500 --> 00:23:39.600
[Amit Varma]: for so long as a colony and a market.

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:40.600
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:23:40.600 --> 00:23:44.280
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote, which is, you know, so therefore, in a sense, you could say that the Bangladeshi

00:23:44.280 --> 00:23:48.440
[Amit Varma]: fight for independence as it became due to circumstances was analogous to the Indian

00:23:48.440 --> 00:23:49.440
[Amit Varma]: fight for independence.

00:23:49.440 --> 00:23:51.240
[Guest]: Yeah, it was analogous to the Indian fight for independence.

00:23:51.240 --> 00:23:54.600
[Guest]: I think the other analogy, of course, is the similar sorts of arguments which are being

00:23:54.600 --> 00:23:58.840
[Guest]: made around the same time in Latin America about dependency theories and so on.

00:23:58.840 --> 00:24:02.760
[Guest]: So you can see that, you know, here, this argument is being extended to a one single

00:24:02.760 --> 00:24:06.520
[Guest]: economy, which, of course, has got these two sort of geographic.

00:24:06.520 --> 00:24:08.080
[Amit Varma]: Just can you elaborate on the Latin American argument?

00:24:08.080 --> 00:24:11.680
[Guest]: I mean, the Latin American argument was primarily to say that, you know, many of these countries,

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:15.440
[Guest]: Latin America, of course, you know, became formally decolonized much before Asia and

00:24:15.440 --> 00:24:16.640
[Guest]: Africa did.

00:24:16.640 --> 00:24:20.680
[Guest]: But the point was to say that, you know, in the post Second World War period, the patterns

00:24:20.680 --> 00:24:25.400
[Guest]: of capitalist development in the Western world was such that areas like Latin America were

00:24:25.400 --> 00:24:29.240
[Guest]: effectively seen as commodity producing in a similar sort of a relation, right?

00:24:29.240 --> 00:24:30.980
[Guest]: So that's not where this thing.

00:24:30.980 --> 00:24:34.320
[Guest]: So there is a sort of a tendency to think that we need to have our own sort of, you

00:24:34.320 --> 00:24:38.480
[Guest]: know, model of economic development, which is kind of independent of this kind of thing.

00:24:38.480 --> 00:24:42.000
[Guest]: However, of course, many economies attempted these import substitution policies during

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:43.000
[Guest]: that period.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:45.840
[Guest]: But what is interesting, of course, is that all of this happening within the context of

00:24:45.840 --> 00:24:46.840
[Guest]: Pakistan, right?

00:24:46.840 --> 00:24:51.120
[Guest]: So the whole argument of a neo-colonial sort of feeling, which Malib's quote captures,

00:24:51.120 --> 00:24:53.760
[Guest]: was one which was being felt by people who belong to the same state.

00:24:53.760 --> 00:24:57.920
[Guest]: So in that sense, it was a much more, I mean, you could have had similar policies in India,

00:24:57.920 --> 00:25:00.640
[Guest]: for instance, but the Indian government of the time, the Nehru government, you know,

00:25:00.640 --> 00:25:04.800
[Guest]: took a conscious decision to enable investment in various parts of India to precisely prevent

00:25:04.800 --> 00:25:09.440
[Guest]: this kind of very lopsided economic growth and development and so on, which the Pakistanis

00:25:09.440 --> 00:25:10.440
[Guest]: never took seriously.

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:15.000
[Guest]: And a lot of that investment did happen in the context of West Pakistan.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:21.080
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about 1968 then, you know, there was youthful revolt in Pakistan.

00:25:21.080 --> 00:25:25.400
[Amit Varma]: And it's not just in Pakistan, it was almost sort of a global thing that, you know, the

00:25:25.400 --> 00:25:29.160
[Amit Varma]: youth was rising up everywhere in America, you had the anti-Vietnam feeling, there was

00:25:29.160 --> 00:25:31.920
[Amit Varma]: this anti-establishment feeling everywhere.

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:34.960
[Amit Varma]: What's going on here, what are the kind of factors that go into something like this?

00:25:34.960 --> 00:25:39.880
[Guest]: Yeah, so 1968 is actually, I think, a good example of how the processes of incipient

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:45.440
[Guest]: globalization came to sort of impact what is happening in the context of Pakistan.

00:25:45.440 --> 00:25:50.400
[Guest]: Because you know, the student revolts of 1968, as you said, was a global phenomenon.

00:25:50.400 --> 00:25:55.120
[Guest]: Of course, everywhere they had local particular sort of issues which were in play.

00:25:55.120 --> 00:25:59.000
[Guest]: But nevertheless, student groups across the world took the cues from one another, right.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:02.000
[Guest]: And it's important to remember just how widespread this was.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.520
[Guest]: And television came to Pakistan in 1968, so they can see everything.

00:26:04.520 --> 00:26:05.520
[Guest]: Right.

00:26:05.520 --> 00:26:08.640
[Guest]: So you had, of course, student revolts happening in the United States, which was also triggered

00:26:08.640 --> 00:26:11.680
[Guest]: by the civil rights, Vietnam War, and that involvement.

00:26:11.680 --> 00:26:15.280
[Guest]: But you had similar things happening in France, in Italy, in Germany.

00:26:15.280 --> 00:26:16.520
[Guest]: You also had it in the Soviet bloc, right.

00:26:16.520 --> 00:26:21.600
[Guest]: In the post 1968, the Czechoslovakia incident, there was, you know, all of that story.

00:26:21.600 --> 00:26:24.760
[Guest]: There was a student movement happening in Japan at the point of time, there was a cultural

00:26:24.760 --> 00:26:28.080
[Guest]: revolution in China, which was again a student sort of led thing.

00:26:28.080 --> 00:26:32.520
[Guest]: So what is happening across the world in some ways was, you know, ricocheting from one place

00:26:32.520 --> 00:26:33.520
[Guest]: to another.

00:26:33.520 --> 00:26:35.440
[Guest]: People were seeing that this kind of mobilization is happening.

00:26:35.440 --> 00:26:39.880
[Guest]: The forms of the mobilization, the vocabularies with local inflections, of course, were still

00:26:39.880 --> 00:26:42.620
[Guest]: quite strikingly reminiscent of one another.

00:26:42.620 --> 00:26:46.600
[Guest]: And what is interesting is that in Pakistan, the student revolts kind of come towards the

00:26:46.600 --> 00:26:48.280
[Guest]: tail end of 1968.

00:26:48.280 --> 00:26:51.600
[Guest]: And as you said, you know, television in Pakistan, people are seeing all of this stuff.

00:26:51.600 --> 00:26:55.000
[Guest]: And of course, there are sort of individuals who also sort of bring the story like, you

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:59.200
[Guest]: know, the sort of famous student revolutionary of the Oxford sit-ins in the British context

00:26:59.200 --> 00:27:02.480
[Guest]: was Tariq Ali, who was from a very well to do Pakistani family.

00:27:02.480 --> 00:27:05.480
[Guest]: And as many student revolutionaries tend to be, yeah.

00:27:05.480 --> 00:27:09.920
[Guest]: And Tariq Ali actually comes back to Pakistan and, you know, and sees that there is this

00:27:09.920 --> 00:27:13.800
[Guest]: whole sort of movement against Ayub Khan's sort of authoritarian regime.

00:27:13.800 --> 00:27:19.040
[Guest]: And what is interesting about the student movement in Pakistan in late 1968, early 1969,

00:27:19.040 --> 00:27:21.720
[Guest]: is that it actually is in both wings of Pakistan.

00:27:21.720 --> 00:27:24.400
[Guest]: It is not as if it's only in the eastern wing of Pakistan, as much in the western wing as

00:27:24.400 --> 00:27:25.400
[Amit Varma]: well.

00:27:25.400 --> 00:27:26.400
[Guest]: But are they coordinating?

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:27.400
[Guest]: Or they're kind of continuous?

00:27:27.400 --> 00:27:28.400
[Guest]: No, no.

00:27:28.400 --> 00:27:31.040
[Guest]: In a sense, they do sort of learn from each other, they sort of express solidarity for

00:27:31.040 --> 00:27:32.040
[Guest]: one another.

00:27:32.040 --> 00:27:33.040
[Amit Varma]: Are they fighting for the same thing?

00:27:33.040 --> 00:27:35.720
[Guest]: Yeah, they all believe that the first step towards thing is true for democratization

00:27:35.720 --> 00:27:36.720
[Guest]: of Pakistan, right?

00:27:36.720 --> 00:27:39.880
[Guest]: So, the authoritarian military government has to go.

00:27:39.880 --> 00:27:44.440
[Guest]: And you know, they see that the first step is to sort of give expression to democracy.

00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:49.000
[Guest]: And of course, you know, they do succeed, Ayub Khan is forced to step down, which I

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:52.120
[Guest]: think is an important accomplishment for student revolutionaries.

00:27:52.120 --> 00:27:55.800
[Guest]: I think they were more successful than almost students anywhere else, possibly with the

00:27:55.800 --> 00:27:57.520
[Amit Varma]: exception of France, where they managed to get de Gaulle.

00:27:57.520 --> 00:28:00.880
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes one feels like a dog chasing a car is finally caught the car, what do you do

00:28:00.880 --> 00:28:01.880
[Guest]: now?

00:28:01.880 --> 00:28:02.880
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly.

00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:03.880
[Guest]: Right.

00:28:03.880 --> 00:28:08.640
[Guest]: So, it is a, it was one of those, you know, situations where they sort of got there.

00:28:08.640 --> 00:28:12.440
[Guest]: And then of course, that sets the stage for not an immediate transfer of power to the

00:28:12.440 --> 00:28:13.440
[Guest]: people.

00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:16.880
[Guest]: But, you know, power, you know, there's a military coup, actually, which deposes Ayub

00:28:16.880 --> 00:28:17.880
[Guest]: Khan.

00:28:17.880 --> 00:28:22.240
[Guest]: So, of course, Yaya Khan comes to power, but very clearly with an agenda of announcing

00:28:22.240 --> 00:28:26.240
[Guest]: elections, and managing some kind of a transition to democracy, which would nevertheless leave

00:28:26.240 --> 00:28:29.000
[Guest]: the military in a controlling sort of position within the polity.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:33.840
[Amit Varma]: And you know, when Yaya announces, Masha Allah, you quote him and saying that the army, quote,

00:28:33.840 --> 00:28:37.880
[Amit Varma]: must be prepared to rule this unfortunate country for the next 14 years or so.

00:28:37.880 --> 00:28:41.080
[Amit Varma]: I simply can't throw this country to the wolves, stop quote.

00:28:41.080 --> 00:28:45.880
[Amit Varma]: And already in his mind, he's, I mean, even though Ayub Khan's resignation and his taking

00:28:45.880 --> 00:28:50.200
[Amit Varma]: over is prompted by the student revolts, he's not taking the students or their demands really

00:28:50.200 --> 00:28:51.200
[Amit Varma]: that seriously.

00:28:51.200 --> 00:28:55.640
[Amit Varma]: He's assumed that this is a period of unrest and the army has to see the country through

00:28:55.640 --> 00:28:57.040
[Amit Varma]: and stabilize it.

00:28:57.040 --> 00:29:00.880
[Amit Varma]: And it's almost like this sense of both entitlement and denial.

00:29:00.880 --> 00:29:01.880
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely.

00:29:01.880 --> 00:29:06.360
[Guest]: I mean, I think Ayub Khan was, you know, for so long seen as such an unimpeachable force

00:29:06.360 --> 00:29:12.840
[Guest]: in Pakistani politics, that, you know, he just couldn't bear to sort of, you know, accept

00:29:12.840 --> 00:29:15.240
[Guest]: what the reality was as it was unfolding.

00:29:15.240 --> 00:29:20.600
[Guest]: But the scale of the revolts, student uprisings, you know, movements by peasants, by various

00:29:20.600 --> 00:29:24.600
[Guest]: kinds of labor unions and so on, was of such a scale that ultimately the Pakistan army

00:29:24.600 --> 00:29:29.440
[Guest]: felt that they had to sort of intervene and persuade Ayub to move out so that, you know,

00:29:29.440 --> 00:29:31.600
[Guest]: they could then restore a modicum of stability.

00:29:31.600 --> 00:29:33.800
[Amit Varma]: So I think it was a very powerful moment at that point of time.

00:29:33.800 --> 00:29:37.600
[Amit Varma]: And there's another telling quote in your book about how the old guard, quote, failed

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:41.680
[Amit Varma]: to feel the pulse of an electorate over half of whom had been born after the hairy days

00:29:41.680 --> 00:29:44.640
[Amit Varma]: of 1947, stop quote.

00:29:44.640 --> 00:29:50.200
[Amit Varma]: And it almost seemed analogous to me as of today, where in India, almost half, more than

00:29:50.200 --> 00:29:52.840
[Amit Varma]: half the people are born after liberalization.

00:29:52.840 --> 00:29:58.960
[Amit Varma]: And yet our politicians on average are like these 60-70 year old fogies who simply don't

00:29:58.960 --> 00:29:59.960
[Amit Varma]: get it.

00:29:59.960 --> 00:30:03.120
[Amit Varma]: And whatever the pulse of the nation is, I'm not saying there is one that would be a simplistic

00:30:03.120 --> 00:30:04.120
[Amit Varma]: narrative.

00:30:04.120 --> 00:30:07.920
[Amit Varma]: But if there was a pulse, those guys who are running the country aren't really equipped

00:30:07.920 --> 00:30:09.240
[Amit Varma]: to get what's going on, right?

00:30:09.240 --> 00:30:10.240
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:30:10.240 --> 00:30:14.520
[Guest]: And the generational gap was kind of one of the major factors for the driver of this thing.

00:30:14.520 --> 00:30:17.600
[Guest]: In a way that actually was in many of the other 1968 revolts.

00:30:17.600 --> 00:30:22.000
[Guest]: But in the context of Pakistan, particularly, I think that was definitely a very important

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:27.200
[Guest]: part of the story, which was to say that, you know, the military and Ayub Khan in particular,

00:30:27.200 --> 00:30:30.720
[Guest]: but even Yahya Khan later, underestimated the extent to which they would be able to

00:30:30.720 --> 00:30:35.400
[Guest]: sort of control these developments or call upon, you know, sort of abstract calls for

00:30:35.400 --> 00:30:40.080
[Guest]: national unity, discipline, etc. as a way of mobilizing and harnessing these energies,

00:30:40.080 --> 00:30:41.700
[Amit Varma]: which proved to be wrong.

00:30:41.700 --> 00:30:44.920
[Amit Varma]: And it seemed to me, correct me if I'm reading it wrong, but it seemed to me that even with

00:30:44.920 --> 00:30:49.000
[Amit Varma]: Mujibur Rahman, who actually eventually got an independent Bangladesh and came to power

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:55.920
[Amit Varma]: because of all of these forces and these ferments, was himself not in control of it at all.

00:30:55.920 --> 00:30:59.720
[Amit Varma]: You know, he was a conventional politician within the framework of Pakistan, he'd been

00:30:59.720 --> 00:31:04.840
[Amit Varma]: a minister and all that, you know, in March 1966, he comes out with a six point program

00:31:04.840 --> 00:31:09.600
[Amit Varma]: for autonomy, where he wants more autonomy, and I suppose more of a federalist structure

00:31:09.600 --> 00:31:12.760
[Amit Varma]: for where Bangladesh has more power within the thing.

00:31:12.760 --> 00:31:17.200
[Amit Varma]: And instead of becoming, you know, the starting tool with which you begin negotiations, that

00:31:17.200 --> 00:31:21.520
[Amit Varma]: becomes a minimum acceptable thing once the movement for Bangladeshi independence gets

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:28.480
[Amit Varma]: going because he is suddenly captive to the wishes of the student revolution and the extremists

00:31:28.480 --> 00:31:29.480
[Amit Varma]: in his party.

00:31:29.480 --> 00:31:30.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:31:30.480 --> 00:31:33.320
[Amit Varma]: And he is forced into all of those strands he might not otherwise take.

00:31:33.320 --> 00:31:34.320
[Guest]: That's I think quite true.

00:31:34.320 --> 00:31:38.320
[Guest]: And I think that transformation is again something that is peculiar to the late 1960s, which

00:31:38.320 --> 00:31:42.200
[Guest]: is why I don't buy into this argument that, you know, Bangladesh was predestined to break

00:31:42.200 --> 00:31:46.040
[Guest]: up because, you know, you had this Bengali majority, which was never given its due and

00:31:46.040 --> 00:31:47.040
[Guest]: so on.

00:31:47.040 --> 00:31:51.840
[Guest]: Actually speaking, for politicians of Mujibur Rahman generation, the real dream was to sort

00:31:51.840 --> 00:31:55.760
[Guest]: of not get an independent state, but to take control of all of Pakistan, which a democratic

00:31:55.760 --> 00:31:58.600
[Guest]: majority could have put them in power, right.

00:31:58.600 --> 00:32:01.680
[Guest]: And as we'll see, you know, even the Indians thought that that actually would not be such

00:32:01.680 --> 00:32:03.320
[Guest]: a bad outcome for their own sort of

00:32:03.320 --> 00:32:04.320
[Guest]: That'd be a great outcome.

00:32:04.320 --> 00:32:06.320
[Guest]: Do you think they'd be fighting with us so much if that was the case?

00:32:06.320 --> 00:32:08.160
[Guest]: Well, so that was the argument at that point in time, right.

00:32:08.160 --> 00:32:11.600
[Guest]: So the assumption was that, listen, the Bengalis are not interested in Kashmir, they are not

00:32:11.600 --> 00:32:14.600
[Guest]: interested in they want better relations with us.

00:32:14.600 --> 00:32:16.160
[Guest]: All of it might have been reasonable assumptions.

00:32:16.160 --> 00:32:19.480
[Guest]: But that's the framework within which people saw, which is why I think it's anachronistic

00:32:19.480 --> 00:32:24.080
[Guest]: to think that that framework was already doomed to sort of, you know, extinction by the time

00:32:24.080 --> 00:32:25.080
[Guest]: that these things were playing out.

00:32:25.080 --> 00:32:26.080
[Guest]: Not at all.

00:32:26.080 --> 00:32:29.080
[Guest]: So in the minds of contemporaries, these were important structures, which you could not

00:32:29.080 --> 00:32:33.280
[Guest]: break away so easily from, you know, it's never an easy thing to be able to do.

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:36.720
[Guest]: It's a bit, actually, I think the best analogy is with, you know, what Jinnah wanted with

00:32:36.720 --> 00:32:39.760
[Guest]: in terms of his Pakistan in, you know, pre-independence India, right?

00:32:39.760 --> 00:32:43.760
[Guest]: I mean, it's not very clear that even he believed that at all points that that outcome

00:32:43.760 --> 00:32:44.760
[Guest]: was likely.

00:32:44.760 --> 00:32:48.920
[Guest]: So, Mujibur Rahman, yes, was very much someone who was there.

00:32:48.920 --> 00:32:51.880
[Guest]: The six-point agenda was very much a federal plan.

00:32:51.880 --> 00:32:55.960
[Guest]: But in a sense, because of the radicalization of the students who then sort of energized

00:32:55.960 --> 00:32:59.800
[Guest]: the Awami League, took it to a very different level and Mujib was a remarkable leader in

00:32:59.800 --> 00:33:00.800
[Guest]: his own right.

00:33:00.800 --> 00:33:03.840
[Guest]: I mean, in a sense, he was, you know, he was able to harness those energies, he was able

00:33:03.840 --> 00:33:09.400
[Guest]: to give them voice and expression in a way that I think was quite remarkable at that

00:33:09.400 --> 00:33:10.400
[Guest]: point of time.

00:33:10.400 --> 00:33:15.760
[Guest]: But yes, he was also hamstrung by the fact that much of the energy behind his sort of

00:33:15.760 --> 00:33:21.080
[Guest]: political party and the six-point demand was now being channeled through younger people

00:33:21.080 --> 00:33:22.440
[Guest]: who wanted more.

00:33:22.440 --> 00:33:25.840
[Amit Varma]: And an interesting analog that comes to mind, I did a recent episode with the historian

00:33:25.840 --> 00:33:28.200
[Amit Varma]: Gyan Prakash in The Emergency.

00:33:28.200 --> 00:33:33.240
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things I sort of learned reading his book was that, I mean, obviously, there

00:33:33.240 --> 00:33:36.920
[Amit Varma]: was similar student sort of unrest in India as well.

00:33:36.920 --> 00:33:42.440
[Amit Varma]: And there, again, when there was a student unrest in 74-75, it starts as a student unrest

00:33:42.440 --> 00:33:46.560
[Amit Varma]: in Bihar with the likes of Lalu and Nitesh, who are the student leaders.

00:33:46.560 --> 00:33:50.380
[Amit Varma]: But it only really gathers momentum when an older leader like Jayaprakash Narayan comes

00:33:50.380 --> 00:33:51.760
[Amit Varma]: and kind of takes it over.

00:33:51.760 --> 00:33:55.680
[Amit Varma]: And it, I mean, again, a similar thing in Bangladesh, where it's a student revolt proper

00:33:55.680 --> 00:33:58.600
[Amit Varma]: and Mujib sort of becomes a figurehead of the thing.

00:33:58.600 --> 00:34:02.520
[Amit Varma]: Is that something common to kind of student movements where they have to, you know?

00:34:02.520 --> 00:34:03.520
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:34:03.520 --> 00:34:06.920
[Guest]: So, you know, the great historian Eric Hobsbawm used to say that, you know, the problem with

00:34:06.920 --> 00:34:09.920
[Guest]: student politics is that, you know, each student generation is only about two or three years

00:34:09.920 --> 00:34:10.920
[Unknown]: in its time.

00:34:10.920 --> 00:34:11.920
[Unknown]: Right?

00:34:11.920 --> 00:34:13.200
[Guest]: It's a transient politics.

00:34:13.200 --> 00:34:18.280
[Guest]: It is difficult to give it kind of institutional structure and framework, which will allow

00:34:18.280 --> 00:34:21.880
[Guest]: it to be played over a reasonable period of time to bring about student change.

00:34:21.880 --> 00:34:25.240
[Guest]: Of course, one way of solving the problem is the way that Indian political parties do,

00:34:25.240 --> 00:34:26.240
[Guest]: right?

00:34:26.240 --> 00:34:28.760
[Guest]: You have these youth wings, which are led by people who are in their 40s, as if any

00:34:28.760 --> 00:34:30.200
[Guest]: of that counts as student politics.

00:34:30.200 --> 00:34:34.640
[Guest]: But the real energy of student politics really is people who believe that, whose idealism

00:34:34.640 --> 00:34:37.720
[Guest]: leads them to believe that, you know, all the structures of possibility can be done

00:34:37.720 --> 00:34:41.480
[Guest]: away with and you can actually aim at something a lot more.

00:34:41.480 --> 00:34:46.400
[Guest]: But that needs to be channelized through formal politics of a certain kind.

00:34:46.400 --> 00:34:48.920
[Guest]: And Mujibur Rahman was, I think, the right man at the right time.

00:34:48.920 --> 00:34:52.160
[Guest]: And, you know, that's partly the reason he's so venerated in Bangladesh.

00:34:52.160 --> 00:34:55.280
[Guest]: I mean, you know, he was named Bongo Bandhu at that point of time.

00:34:55.280 --> 00:35:00.400
[Guest]: And partly because, you know, he was a phenomenal orator, a very charismatic leader, someone

00:35:00.400 --> 00:35:04.960
[Guest]: who understood what the needs of the time were, but was still trying to see if there

00:35:04.960 --> 00:35:09.160
[Guest]: could be some way out, which did not involve excessive sort of violence and bloodshed and

00:35:09.160 --> 00:35:10.160
[Guest]: so on.

00:35:10.160 --> 00:35:13.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, another interesting sort of learning that came up on me from your book

00:35:13.840 --> 00:35:19.360
[Amit Varma]: was that contrary to popular hindsight perception, it's not like Mujib wanted independence from

00:35:19.360 --> 00:35:20.360
[Amit Varma]: the start.

00:35:20.360 --> 00:35:24.360
[Amit Varma]: And, and even later, as we find, it's not like Indira was this great warrior who wanted

00:35:24.360 --> 00:35:29.120
[Amit Varma]: to bring Bangladesh to independence, they were both almost very reluctant for a long

00:35:29.120 --> 00:35:32.240
[Amit Varma]: part of that journey till events force themselves upon these two people.

00:35:32.240 --> 00:35:37.560
[Guest]: Yeah, I think that's certainly true of Mujibur Rahman, see, because the elections of 1970,

00:35:37.560 --> 00:35:40.840
[Guest]: by the time the election results come out in December 1970, it is very clear that the

00:35:40.840 --> 00:35:42.800
[Guest]: Awami League is the single largest party.

00:35:42.800 --> 00:35:46.960
[Guest]: But there is a structural problem in as much as the Awami League has won pretty much every

00:35:46.960 --> 00:35:51.320
[Guest]: seat in East Pakistan, barring two, but has won no seat in West Pakistan.

00:35:51.320 --> 00:35:55.980
[Guest]: And the biggest West Pakistani party was Pakistan's People's Party, PPP, which still exists.

00:35:55.980 --> 00:36:01.320
[Guest]: Then a new party recently founded by Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto, which had did a reasonably good

00:36:01.320 --> 00:36:05.520
[Guest]: showing in West Pakistan, but managed to sort of do almost nothing in the East.

00:36:05.520 --> 00:36:08.400
[Guest]: So there was this kind of cleavage between these two sides, in a sense that there was

00:36:08.400 --> 00:36:13.220
[Guest]: no political force, which was able to bridge this kind of East West barrier, so to speak.

00:36:13.220 --> 00:36:17.720
[Guest]: But if you were talking about a normal parliamentary system of democracy, the natural thing would

00:36:17.720 --> 00:36:21.600
[Guest]: have been to invite the leader of the largest party to form government, and that is precisely

00:36:21.600 --> 00:36:24.840
[Guest]: what Mujib and the Awami League were hoping would happen.

00:36:24.840 --> 00:36:29.120
[Guest]: But the army and, you know, Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto had different plans, and so things took a

00:36:29.120 --> 00:36:30.120
[Guest]: very different turn.

00:36:30.120 --> 00:36:33.280
[Amit Varma]: So Yahya was almost blindsided by the results, he didn't expect it.

00:36:33.280 --> 00:36:37.040
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, because he, you know, gave his prognosis to the Americans who trusted him

00:36:37.040 --> 00:36:39.000
[Amit Varma]: so much, even they were blindsided by it.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:45.120
[Guest]: Well, I think everyone was taken to a greater or lesser extent by the, you know, by surprise

00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:48.240
[Guest]: of the outcome, particularly of the Awami League's sort of extraordinary performance

00:36:48.240 --> 00:36:49.240
[Guest]: in the East.

00:36:49.240 --> 00:36:53.000
[Guest]: You know, I think that was something that the Pakistan army did not foresee.

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:57.360
[Guest]: And of course, the Pakistan military and its intelligence agencies had, you know, had done

00:36:57.360 --> 00:37:01.040
[Guest]: their homework before the elections to make sure that, you know, the outcome would not

00:37:01.040 --> 00:37:03.440
[Guest]: be very unfavorable to what they wanted.

00:37:03.440 --> 00:37:06.640
[Guest]: But that turned out to be entirely wrong and, you know, they were caught in a situation

00:37:06.640 --> 00:37:10.680
[Guest]: which they quite did not anticipate would come out.

00:37:10.680 --> 00:37:13.800
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about Bhutto here, who's the other major player in this, you know,

00:37:13.800 --> 00:37:20.040
[Amit Varma]: seems to me almost as this sort of immoral genius who is ultimately, as we know in history

00:37:20.040 --> 00:37:23.400
[Amit Varma]: by hindsight, foiled by his own petard.

00:37:23.400 --> 00:37:27.160
[Amit Varma]: But what kind of person is he and what's the role that he's playing here?

00:37:27.160 --> 00:37:28.480
[Amit Varma]: What does he want out of all this?

00:37:28.480 --> 00:37:31.760
[Amit Varma]: Because he's also been a conventional politician long before this.

00:37:31.760 --> 00:37:34.360
[Amit Varma]: He's been with Ayub Khan, he's been a minister and so on.

00:37:34.360 --> 00:37:39.160
[Guest]: Yeah, so Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto is, you know, is at least in sheer terms of his political

00:37:39.160 --> 00:37:42.960
[Guest]: skill a human, you know, something bordering on genius in terms of the way that he was

00:37:42.960 --> 00:37:44.800
[Guest]: able to rise through the Pakistani system.

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:49.280
[Guest]: You know, here was someone who sort of began working in the Ayub Khan administration as

00:37:49.280 --> 00:37:53.480
[Guest]: a junior minister, then became very important, became, you know, effectively sort of, you

00:37:53.480 --> 00:37:58.120
[Guest]: know, in charge of foreign affairs in that context, egged Ayub Khan to sort of attack

00:37:58.120 --> 00:37:59.960
[Guest]: India in 1965.

00:37:59.960 --> 00:38:04.920
[Guest]: And then when the war went pear shaped, actually turned around against his old patron, saying

00:38:04.920 --> 00:38:09.120
[Guest]: that, you know, Pakistan had been let down and so on, and then went on to find the Pakistan

00:38:09.120 --> 00:38:15.240
[Guest]: People's Party, you know, came up with a political style and platform, which was an interesting

00:38:15.240 --> 00:38:19.200
[Guest]: amalgam of the left and the sort of right and so on, nationalist, but also very leftist,

00:38:19.200 --> 00:38:24.280
[Guest]: you know, because of his role in Pakistan's outreach to China post 1962, the war between

00:38:24.280 --> 00:38:28.320
[Guest]: India and China, you know, the leftists were always sort of very wary of taking him on

00:38:28.320 --> 00:38:31.880
[Guest]: because he was seen as someone who had, you know, those links with China and so on.

00:38:31.880 --> 00:38:37.440
[Guest]: So and it was an extraordinary demagogue, someone who was a very charismatic figure,

00:38:37.440 --> 00:38:41.560
[Guest]: who was able to sort of tap into both older forms of politics, you know, he himself came

00:38:41.560 --> 00:38:46.760
[Guest]: from Sindh, you know, so he was sort of a very important landlord in the Sindh context,

00:38:46.760 --> 00:38:51.200
[Guest]: had all those other, you know, sort of, you know, the religious leadership and the landed

00:38:51.200 --> 00:38:53.080
[Guest]: leadership there has sort of very close ties.

00:38:53.080 --> 00:38:57.320
[Guest]: So he was able to draw on those kinds of tropes of conducting himself, but at the same time

00:38:57.320 --> 00:39:01.480
[Guest]: could also mouth all this sort of radical slogan of roti kapda or makaan, which, you

00:39:01.480 --> 00:39:02.480
[Amit Varma]: know, he said,

00:39:02.480 --> 00:39:06.120
[Amit Varma]: Which I was amazed to, I saw it, I said, no, no, either Indira said it or is from Bollywood,

00:39:06.120 --> 00:39:12.240
[Guest]: it cannot possibly be, but it is very much his and he was able to craft a political movement,

00:39:12.240 --> 00:39:17.520
[Guest]: which in a very short span of time, was able to sort of, you know, create a position for

00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:19.200
[Guest]: itself, which is quite remarkable.

00:39:19.200 --> 00:39:22.240
[Guest]: It is all the more remarkable because, you know, he had to do it, obviously, under the

00:39:22.240 --> 00:39:26.320
[Guest]: constraints of operating under a military rule of various kinds and someone whom he

00:39:26.320 --> 00:39:28.520
[Guest]: had himself alienated, which is Ayub Khan.

00:39:28.520 --> 00:39:34.480
[Guest]: So I think, you know, Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto was quite a remarkable figure in his time,

00:39:34.480 --> 00:39:36.360
[Guest]: both during the war, but also subsequently.

00:39:36.360 --> 00:39:39.760
[Guest]: And I think, you know, Pakistani history is yet to give him his due in not in a sense

00:39:39.760 --> 00:39:40.920
[Guest]: of appreciating his achievements.

00:39:40.920 --> 00:39:45.520
[Guest]: I think he was a very mercurial figure with some, you know, really sort of, you know,

00:39:45.520 --> 00:39:47.320
[Guest]: nasty things to his credit as well.

00:39:47.320 --> 00:39:51.080
[Guest]: But just acknowledging his importance as a historical figure in the history of Pakistan,

00:39:51.080 --> 00:39:54.840
[Guest]: I think that that angle of it needs to be, you know, dealt with further by historians.

00:39:54.840 --> 00:39:56.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, moral genius went a long way.

00:39:56.400 --> 00:40:01.120
[Amit Varma]: And as you mentioned, who could as a politician be all things to all people, which, you know,

00:40:01.120 --> 00:40:05.320
[Amit Varma]: is a skill Narendra Modi himself kind of demonstrated in 2014.

00:40:05.320 --> 00:40:07.880
[Amit Varma]: We don't know how much of it will sort of carry over.

00:40:07.880 --> 00:40:12.120
[Amit Varma]: So tell me, so the elections are over at the end of 70.

00:40:12.120 --> 00:40:15.040
[Amit Varma]: And Yahya is kind of blindsided by the whole result.

00:40:15.040 --> 00:40:18.560
[Amit Varma]: And even Bhutto isn't extremely happy because you know, what the hell, I mean, the Awami

00:40:18.560 --> 00:40:22.920
[Amit Varma]: League has just got many more seats than him and he's going to have to deal with them at

00:40:22.920 --> 00:40:23.920
[Amit Varma]: some point.

00:40:23.920 --> 00:40:29.040
[Amit Varma]: And he had assumed that it will be like, he'll be the politician who will rule Pakistan with

00:40:29.040 --> 00:40:30.400
[Amit Varma]: the army at his wings.

00:40:30.400 --> 00:40:34.720
[Amit Varma]: So I think you quote somewhere in the book where he tells Yahya that I'll be the politician,

00:40:34.720 --> 00:40:37.080
[Amit Varma]: you'll be the general, and they'll kind of rule together.

00:40:37.080 --> 00:40:38.440
[Amit Varma]: And all that's gone.

00:40:38.440 --> 00:40:43.840
[Amit Varma]: And both Yahya and Bhutto now sort of collude to stop Mujib from taking over.

00:40:43.840 --> 00:40:47.040
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about, you know, those months when that collusion is active.

00:40:47.040 --> 00:40:52.400
[Guest]: Yeah, so that effectively happens between January and late March 1971 is the period

00:40:52.400 --> 00:40:56.520
[Guest]: of post election sort of wrangling and negotiations.

00:40:56.520 --> 00:40:59.280
[Guest]: In a sense, stuff which would never have happened, I mean, in any parliamentary democracy, the

00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:03.320
[Guest]: only job for Yahya Khan would have been to sort of convene the sort of National Assembly

00:41:03.320 --> 00:41:05.960
[Guest]: and they also wanted to have a Constituent Assembly and so on, you know, whatever it

00:41:05.960 --> 00:41:08.960
[Guest]: was Mujibur Rahman should have been invited to form the government.

00:41:08.960 --> 00:41:14.000
[Guest]: But instead of that, they sort of tried to get Mujibur Rahman to accept what the outlines

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:18.240
[Guest]: of a future constitutional settlement would be primarily with a view to securing the army's

00:41:18.240 --> 00:41:23.480
[Guest]: own role and getting assurances from him before anything else could be done.

00:41:23.480 --> 00:41:27.640
[Guest]: And those negotiations then sort of went nowhere.

00:41:27.640 --> 00:41:32.480
[Guest]: And in that time, Bhutto very quickly insinuated himself into the picture by saying that, you

00:41:32.480 --> 00:41:36.760
[Guest]: know, he was not the army's favorite when this whole story began.

00:41:36.760 --> 00:41:40.680
[Guest]: But by the time the sort of negotiations are kind of in the middle, Bhutto is able to play

00:41:40.680 --> 00:41:44.080
[Guest]: spoiler by telling the army on the one hand that, listen, if you're going to do this kind

00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:48.240
[Guest]: of a deal and allow them to come without assurances for the West Pakistanis and so on, it's going

00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:49.240
[Guest]: to be a non-starter.

00:41:49.240 --> 00:41:52.040
[Guest]: So he's on the one hand, raising the stakes constantly.

00:41:52.040 --> 00:41:54.760
[Guest]: But on the other hand, he's also giving them indications saying that, listen, we cannot

00:41:54.760 --> 00:41:57.800
[Guest]: adopt what he calls a Turkish model at that point of time, right, I mean, Turkey's a sort

00:41:57.800 --> 00:42:01.920
[Guest]: of example of the Islamic country that, you know, they sort of wanted to be, which is

00:42:01.920 --> 00:42:05.320
[Guest]: that to say that, you know, you have the military, but you also have civilians and, you know,

00:42:05.320 --> 00:42:09.680
[Guest]: you have some kind of a modesty when I working out at that point of time.

00:42:09.680 --> 00:42:17.000
[Guest]: And so, in a sense, effectively, Yahya and the military regime and Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:22.600
[Guest]: converge towards this point where they finally come to a decision that, you know, Mujibur

00:42:22.600 --> 00:42:27.840
[Guest]: Rahman has to be stopped in his tracks, and that this moment for the creation of, you

00:42:27.840 --> 00:42:33.120
[Guest]: know, a new polity where Mujib and the Awami League would play such an important role,

00:42:33.120 --> 00:42:38.560
[Guest]: and the Punjabis and the West Pakistan military, etc, is going to be downgraded in its importance,

00:42:38.560 --> 00:42:40.560
[Guest]: should not be allowed to pass.

00:42:40.560 --> 00:42:43.960
[Guest]: And it's at that moment that, you know, things really start going downhill.

00:42:43.960 --> 00:42:48.320
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, there's a funky quote a little when the crisis is a little later on, probably

00:42:48.320 --> 00:42:52.760
[Amit Varma]: from March, where a senior general tells Yahya Khan, quote, don't worry, we won't allow these

00:42:52.760 --> 00:42:55.960
[Amit Varma]: black bastards to rule over us, stop quote.

00:42:55.960 --> 00:43:00.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's very clear even at that point that Yahya doesn't want to sort of respect the

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:03.440
[Amit Varma]: democratic expression and, you know, he's trying to control the process.

00:43:03.440 --> 00:43:05.360
[Amit Varma]: What is the outcome he's actually aiming for?

00:43:05.360 --> 00:43:09.400
[Guest]: I mean, I think, I mean, it's again difficult to say, because, you know, nowhere is it very

00:43:09.400 --> 00:43:10.400
[Guest]: clearly laid down.

00:43:10.400 --> 00:43:13.240
[Guest]: These were all things which were done under the guise of coming up with some kind of a

00:43:13.240 --> 00:43:15.160
[Guest]: constitutional arrangement and so on.

00:43:15.160 --> 00:43:20.280
[Guest]: But I think what Yahya would have been sort of quite satisfied with was a, if you know,

00:43:20.280 --> 00:43:24.800
[Guest]: you came up with some structure where he remained president, where the army's budgets and its

00:43:24.800 --> 00:43:29.280
[Guest]: control over sort of, you know, various kinds of important policy issues remained outside

00:43:29.280 --> 00:43:32.560
[Guest]: the purview of democratic politics.

00:43:32.560 --> 00:43:37.240
[Guest]: And then basically, you know, as long as Sayyed Mujib was willing to, you know, take on board

00:43:37.240 --> 00:43:41.400
[Guest]: some, you know, West Pakistani sort of representation in his government and so on.

00:43:41.400 --> 00:43:44.280
[Guest]: So, in a sense, those were the kinds of things that he wanted to do.

00:43:44.280 --> 00:43:49.400
[Guest]: But in effect, all of that would have meant, from Mujib's standpoint, a significant dilution

00:43:49.400 --> 00:43:53.760
[Guest]: of the issues on which the election were fought and won by the Awami League.

00:43:53.760 --> 00:43:58.960
[Amit Varma]: Especially because, you know, now because of the radicalism of a lot of his support,

00:43:58.960 --> 00:44:02.640
[Amit Varma]: the student movement and all of that, he's kind of forced into a corner where he has

00:44:02.640 --> 00:44:10.840
[Amit Varma]: to insist on the six point charter that he laid out for Bangladeshi autonomy as a minimum

00:44:10.840 --> 00:44:12.880
[Amit Varma]: condition that without that he cannot proceed.

00:44:12.880 --> 00:44:15.020
[Amit Varma]: And he's kind of forced into this corner.

00:44:15.020 --> 00:44:19.080
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, the army cannot accept that either, because Yaya, self-interest, he's

00:44:19.080 --> 00:44:22.520
[Amit Varma]: trying to, you know, consolidate his own position.

00:44:22.520 --> 00:44:25.360
[Amit Varma]: And on the side, you have Bhutto playing Yaya.

00:44:25.360 --> 00:44:31.760
[Amit Varma]: And I presume there's a fair degree of sort of West Pakistani, Urdu speaking, condescension

00:44:31.760 --> 00:44:37.000
[Amit Varma]: towards these, you know, these Bangladeshi, Bengali, East Pakistanis.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:38.000
[Guest]: That's right.

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:41.000
[Guest]: I mean, I think that cultural angle of it comes out quite clearly in the quote that

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:42.000
[Guest]: you mentioned.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:47.880
[Guest]: You know, that there is a strong condescension of Bengalis as somehow being culturally, physically,

00:44:47.880 --> 00:44:52.880
[Guest]: and in every way inferior to the sort of, you know, the West Pakistanis and so on, particularly

00:44:52.880 --> 00:44:53.880
[Guest]: the Punjabis.

00:44:53.880 --> 00:44:56.440
[Guest]: So, there was very much that angle to it.

00:44:56.440 --> 00:45:00.640
[Guest]: And in fact, that was part of the reason why once the military crackdown began, you know,

00:45:00.640 --> 00:45:05.760
[Guest]: some of it is really hard, because that kind of ethnic angle to, you know, that story becomes

00:45:05.760 --> 00:45:08.440
[Guest]: much more important once the crackdown begins.

00:45:08.440 --> 00:45:11.560
[Amit Varma]: And how do those events play out like around March 71?

00:45:11.560 --> 00:45:17.120
[Amit Varma]: How do events take Mujib from a position of still trying to negotiate with Yaya Khan to

00:45:17.120 --> 00:45:19.560
[Amit Varma]: actually going ahead and declaring independence?

00:45:19.560 --> 00:45:26.000
[Guest]: Well, the reality is that, you know, the convening of the National Assembly is postponed, adjourned,

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:30.080
[Guest]: sine die, you know, for, you know, without a sort of any date that then leads to a sort

00:45:30.080 --> 00:45:33.640
[Guest]: of upsurge on the streets in Bangladesh.

00:45:33.640 --> 00:45:36.680
[Guest]: And from that point on, Mujib has to play a careful role, right?

00:45:36.680 --> 00:45:41.760
[Guest]: So, on the one hand, he has to keep the momentum and the upsurge going, because it allows him

00:45:41.760 --> 00:45:44.400
[Guest]: to put pressure on the West Pakistanis.

00:45:44.400 --> 00:45:48.520
[Guest]: But at the same time, he doesn't want to be in a position where the Pakistan army believes

00:45:48.520 --> 00:45:52.400
[Guest]: that the situation is getting so out of control, that the only option is to use force to sort

00:45:52.400 --> 00:45:53.400
[Guest]: of put them down.

00:45:53.400 --> 00:45:54.400
[Guest]: Right?

00:45:54.400 --> 00:45:56.560
[Guest]: So, he's trying to sort of balance both of these.

00:45:56.560 --> 00:46:00.560
[Guest]: There are other problems as well, in a sense that there are non-Bengalis in East Pakistan

00:46:00.560 --> 00:46:04.240
[Guest]: who are being targeted by the Bengalis, as partly because they were seen as Tujus.

00:46:04.240 --> 00:46:07.640
[Guest]: So there's another one more layer of ethnic complexity to this.

00:46:07.640 --> 00:46:12.560
[Guest]: Many of these are Urdu speaking migrants from Eastern India, like Bihar and other parts

00:46:12.560 --> 00:46:13.760
[Guest]: of Eastern India and so on.

00:46:13.760 --> 00:46:18.520
[Guest]: So, he has to keep those kinds of, you know, violence and that kind of tendencies under

00:46:18.520 --> 00:46:19.520
[Guest]: check.

00:46:19.520 --> 00:46:21.200
[Guest]: So, it's a very difficult time for him.

00:46:21.200 --> 00:46:26.120
[Guest]: And this is also the time when he's tentatively sending feelers to India saying, listen, you

00:46:26.120 --> 00:46:30.480
[Guest]: know, if the Indians were to sort of, you know, make some noises and tell the Pakistanis

00:46:30.480 --> 00:46:34.440
[Guest]: that, you know, we will disapprove of any use of force, etc., then, you know, maybe

00:46:34.440 --> 00:46:35.440
[Guest]: the Pakistanis will back off.

00:46:35.440 --> 00:46:37.800
[Guest]: So, and then he's trying to tell similar things to the Americans.

00:46:37.800 --> 00:46:42.280
[Guest]: So, Mujib is trying pretty much everything, trick in the book to make sure that he can

00:46:42.280 --> 00:46:47.520
[Guest]: come out of the situation, either, you know, with a sort of mandate to form government

00:46:47.520 --> 00:46:51.600
[Guest]: or at least some kind of a power sharing arrangement without tipping over into violence.

00:46:51.600 --> 00:46:52.960
[Guest]: And that is what is his thing.

00:46:52.960 --> 00:46:57.840
[Guest]: But the Pakistanis are very clear that, at least from about the first week of March onwards,

00:46:57.840 --> 00:47:02.320
[Guest]: that talks are simply a fig leaf behind which, a smoke screen behind which they will carry

00:47:02.320 --> 00:47:03.320
[Guest]: on the military buildup.

00:47:03.320 --> 00:47:08.560
[Guest]: There was not that much of Pakistani military presence in what later became Bangladesh.

00:47:08.560 --> 00:47:10.280
[Guest]: They had to sort of do a buildup.

00:47:10.280 --> 00:47:14.080
[Guest]: That buildup was also kind of a little difficult for them to do because India and Pakistan,

00:47:14.080 --> 00:47:17.560
[Guest]: because their own sort of problems, Indians had shut off their airspace to Pakistani.

00:47:17.560 --> 00:47:20.840
[Guest]: So the Pakistanis had to do that buildup by going through Sri Lanka, you know, so Colombo

00:47:20.840 --> 00:47:23.120
[Guest]: was a transit point between the two wings.

00:47:23.120 --> 00:47:25.280
[Guest]: So, all of that took a little bit of time.

00:47:25.280 --> 00:47:29.200
[Guest]: And of course, they wanted to keep the element of surprise and they decided that when they

00:47:29.200 --> 00:47:31.040
[Amit Varma]: would crack down, they would hit really hard.

00:47:31.040 --> 00:47:35.320
[Amit Varma]: And Jaya was kind of pretending that he's still interested in talks with Mujib while

00:47:35.320 --> 00:47:39.360
[Amit Varma]: on the one hand, the military buildup is proceeding and he knows he's going to crack down.

00:47:39.360 --> 00:47:43.180
[Amit Varma]: So you know, Operation Searchlight, as it's called, starts on March 25th.

00:47:43.180 --> 00:47:46.720
[Amit Varma]: At what point does it become an inevitability that it is going to happen?

00:47:46.720 --> 00:47:47.720
[Guest]: There's no telling.

00:47:47.720 --> 00:47:50.400
[Guest]: Well, I think already, you know, a few days before that it is becoming, you know, in fact,

00:47:50.400 --> 00:47:54.220
[Guest]: in those few days, if you just look at the records of the negotiations which are happening,

00:47:54.220 --> 00:47:57.960
[Guest]: it seems as if great progress is being made, you know, and in fact, you know, there's a

00:47:57.960 --> 00:47:58.960
[Guest]: lot of sense.

00:47:58.960 --> 00:48:04.160
[Guest]: And in fact, Mujib's own sort of trusted lieutenants within the Awami League are very conflicted

00:48:04.160 --> 00:48:05.320
[Guest]: about how this is going to play.

00:48:05.320 --> 00:48:09.080
[Guest]: Because on the one hand, it suddenly seems like, you know, progress is happening.

00:48:09.080 --> 00:48:13.520
[Guest]: So you know, you don't want to sort of, you know, unnecessarily sort of burn that bridge.

00:48:13.520 --> 00:48:16.140
[Guest]: You want to try and see if things can sort of move on.

00:48:16.140 --> 00:48:19.680
[Guest]: But at the same time, you know, they have their own doubts and concerns.

00:48:19.680 --> 00:48:23.360
[Guest]: And in fact, just around the time when the operation begins, you know, people tell Mujib

00:48:23.360 --> 00:48:26.880
[Guest]: and Rahman that, listen, you have to sort of basically leave the country.

00:48:26.880 --> 00:48:32.280
[Guest]: And Mujib takes a call saying that, you know, if he sort of flees, then the Pakistanis are

00:48:32.280 --> 00:48:34.900
[Guest]: going to really get after his people.

00:48:34.900 --> 00:48:38.600
[Guest]: And he says that, no, you know, it's just not possible for me to sort of take that kind

00:48:38.600 --> 00:48:39.600
[Guest]: of a move.

00:48:39.600 --> 00:48:40.600
[Amit Varma]: And then he's captured by the Pakistanis.

00:48:40.600 --> 00:48:46.400
[Amit Varma]: Is that a principle stand or is he sort of just or he underestimates the inevitability

00:48:46.400 --> 00:48:47.400
[Amit Varma]: of the military crackdown?

00:48:47.400 --> 00:48:50.360
[Guest]: Well, I mean, at that point, by that point of time, you know, by the time this kind of

00:48:50.360 --> 00:48:52.320
[Guest]: discussion is happening, the military crackdown is already underway.

00:48:52.320 --> 00:48:54.720
[Amit Varma]: So he just chooses to.

00:48:54.720 --> 00:48:59.640
[Guest]: So he just chooses to say that, listen, instead of making it, you know, his own survival and

00:48:59.640 --> 00:49:04.800
[Guest]: issue on which the Pakistanis will crack down very hard on the rest of the Bengali people,

00:49:04.800 --> 00:49:09.200
[Guest]: it is better that, you know, he sort of takes a stand and decides what he wants to do and

00:49:09.200 --> 00:49:10.200
[Guest]: so on.

00:49:10.200 --> 00:49:13.440
[Amit Varma]: So we'll take a quick break at this point and we'll come back to talk about India and

00:49:13.440 --> 00:49:24.200
[Unknown]: the rest of the world.

00:49:24.200 --> 00:49:45.200
[Unknown]: But

00:49:45.200 --> 00:49:47.720
[Unknown]: also joins in to talk about his discovery of a bazaar.

